library(dplyr)

We will also want to create a couple of unique functions that I have found useful in my own data analyses

# This grabs n characters from the RIGHT side of a character variable
substrRight <- function(x, n){
  substr(x, nchar(x)-n+1, nchar(x))
}
# This grabs n characters from the LEFT side of a character variable
substrLeft <- function(x, n){
  substr(x, 1, n)
}
# This works just similar to %in% but selects what is NOT %in% instead
'%!in%'<-function(x,y)!('%in%'(x,y))

This will create the URLs and destination paths (i.e., the place you want to put your file) for the data

The “for” loop will iteratively pair our URLs and destinations to pull them from my GitHub repository

  • for (i in 1:20) indicates that i will be equal to a series of numbers from 1 to 20 in the loop
  • Anytime an i appears in the functions placed within the loop, it will substitute the currently selected number

Test out what the result will be by:

  1. setting i to a particular number (i.e.,i <- 1) and then
  2. testing out the code within the for loop (i.e., just enter the download.file(urls[i],destfile = destinations[i]) part)
for (i in 1:20){
  download.file(urls[i],destfile = destinations[i])
}

Now that our data is read into the R environment, lets put them all in lists so we can manipulate them all simulaneously.

  • It’s possible to do this file by file as well, but it would also significantly increase the amount of lines of code we would need (i.e., this is more elegant)
  • Since we have two different data formats we need to treat them differently before it’s possible to join them together
df_list_wide<-list("g1_t24"=g1_t24,"g2_t24"=g2_t24,"g3_t24"=g3_t24,"g4_t24"=g4_t24,"g5_t24"=g5_t24,"g6_t24"=g6_t24,"g2_t48"=g2_t48,"g3_t48"=g3_t48,"g4_t48"=g4_t48,"g5_t48"=g5_t48,"g6_t48"=g6_t48)

str(df_list_wide)

After creating a list of the wide format, let’s convert them to long format using the melt() function

df_list_wide.m<-lapply(df_list_wide, function(x) melt(x, id.vars =  "rowID"))

- How did that change the data’s format? (use str() to take a look)

- Does it look like the format of the 72 hour data frames yet?

Here we use a for loop to iteratively perform a series of commands

  • Consider this phrase df_list_wide.m[[i]]. Based on what you know of lists, what will this command give you as you cycle through each time?
  • What about df_list_wide.m[[i]][,1]?
for (i in 1:11){
  df_list_wide.m[[i]][,1]<-paste0(df_list_wide.m[[i]][,1],gsub("X","",df_list_wide.m[[i]][,2])) # combining row name with column number with `paste0`
  df_list_wide.m[[i]]<-df_list_wide.m[[i]][c(1,3)]
  df_list_wide.m[i]<-lapply(df_list_wide.m[i], function(x) setnames(x,c("wellID",paste0("time_",substrRight(names(df_list_wide.m[i]),2))))) # using `substrRight` we are renaming each of the columns in the data frames wellID, and then time_XX. XX will be the right-most two characters of the dataframe name which are the time point in hours); we also use `setnames` to change the column names
  
} # note that the for loop doesn't end until down here

Do we have the correct data format now?

Let’s make a list of the long format data

df_list_long<-list("g1_t48"=g1_t48,"g1_t72"=g1_t72,"g2_t72"=g2_t72,"g3_t72"=g3_t72,"g4_t72"=g4_t72,"g5_t72"=g5_t72,"g6_t72"=g6_t72)

And run a for loop to relabel the columns in these data frames as well

for (i in 1:7){
  df_list_long[i]<-lapply(df_list_long[i], function(x) setnames(x,c("wellID",paste0("time_",substrRight(names(df_list_long[i]),2)))))
}

Success! Our data can now be combined!!

df_list.f<-c(df_list_wide.m,df_list_long)

str(df_list.f)

Let’s add in our carbohydrate information before subsetting it based on groups using the merge() function

df_list.f<-lapply(df_list.f, function(x) merge(x, key, by.all = "wellID", sort=FALSE))

str(df_list.f)

Subsetting by Group

In this section we will pull out each individual group data into it’s own dataframe and prepare it for plotting

# Group 1's data
g1_list<-c(df_list.f["g1_t24"],df_list.f["g1_t48"],df_list.f["g1_t72"]) # making a list of all of group 1's timepoints

g1_data<-Reduce(function(x,y) merge(x, y, all= TRUE), g1_list) # merging these together into one data frame

Take a look at the new data frame using a few different commands we have learned (i.e., head(), tail(), str(), colnames())

Now that we have a useable data frame, let’s select carbon sources where we had a positive growth result (i.e., there was enough to cause reduction of the tetrazolium dye in the Biolog plates)

  • I chose an arbitrary cut-off of a 0.2 OD increase from the 24 hr time point
  • In this command I use conditional formatting to select for OD values with that increase and identify the carbon sources where that occurred
g1_carbon<-unique(g1_data[g1_data$time_72 >= (g1_data$time_24+0.2),]$carbon_source)

print(g1_carbon)

Let’s subset our data to only include the carbon sources we just identified

g1_pos<-g1_data[g1_data$carbon_source %in% g1_carbon,]

Finally, we will convert our data frame into a long format, since that’s what ggplot prefers

  • We can also grab the right 2 characters of the variable column in our data frame using substrRight since that will be time; we can then turn those into numbers with as.numeric
g1_pos.m<-melt(g1_pos, id.vars=c("wellID","carbon_source"))
g1_pos.m$variable<-as.numeric(substrRight(as.character(g1_pos.m$variable),2))

Plotting our data (at last!)

Let’s create a theme that we can call in each plot

  • Here is where we change things like font size, axis line colors, etc.)
  • This will also streamline each plot by reducing redundant code
  • Take a look at each line within the theme() function, after we make plots in a second, revisit each of these and delete particular lines and see how they affect your plot
my_theme<-theme_bw() + theme(axis.line=element_line(color="black"),
                             panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
                             panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
                             panel.border = element_blank(),
                             panel.background = element_blank(),
                             text=element_text(size = 12))

Now that we have a theme, let’s create our plot:

  • Remember, ggplot uses layers, so we will build those layers on top of each other to gradually fill out the plot we want
# Let's create an empty plot
growth_all.p<-ggplot(data_forplot,aes(x=variable,y=value,color=carbon_source,group=carbon_source,fill=carbon_source))

plot(growth_all.p)

Adding our data points with geom_jitter()

growth_all.p<-ggplot(data_forplot,aes(x=variable,y=value,color=carbon_source,group=carbon_source,fill=carbon_source))+
  geom_jitter()

plot(growth_all.p)

Those data points are chaotic, we could either

  • plot with geom_point() instead
  • add a width parameter inside geom_jitter()
growth_all.p<-ggplot(data_forplot,aes(x=variable,y=value,color=carbon_source,group=carbon_source,fill=carbon_source))+
  geom_jitter(width=0.2)

plot(growth_all.p) # are data points are less spread out but not completely overlapping

With all of the data points though, it is difficult to see trends. So, let’s add a trend line with stat_summary()

  • stat_summary uses the mean our data at each time point
growth_all.p<-ggplot(data_forplot,aes(x=variable,y=value,color=carbon_source,group=carbon_source,fill=carbon_source))+geom_jitter(width=0.2)+
  stat_summary(fun=mean, geom="line", size=1)

plot(growth_all.p)

Using a variant of stat_summary() we can add the mean standard error (mean_se) in a semi-transparent ribbon along our lines

growth_all.p<-ggplot(data_forplot,aes(x=variable,y=value,color=carbon_source,group=carbon_source,fill=carbon_source))+geom_jitter(width=0.2)+
  stat_summary(fun=mean, geom="line", size=1)+
  stat_summary(fun.data = mean_se,geom="ribbon",color="transparent",alpha=0.3)

plot(growth_all.p)

That’s pretty messy, so let’s plot each carbon source individually with facet_wrap()

growth_all.p<-ggplot(data_forplot,aes(x=variable,y=value,color=carbon_source,group=carbon_source,fill=carbon_source))+geom_jitter(width=0.2)+
  stat_summary(fun=mean, geom="line", size=1)+
  stat_summary(fun.data = mean_se,geom="ribbon",color="transparent",alpha=0.3)+
  facet_wrap(~carbon_source)

plot(growth_all.p)

Last but not least, let’s polish up our plot a little by adding better axis labels

growth_all.p<-ggplot(data_forplot,aes(x=variable,y=value,color=carbon_source,group=carbon_source,fill=carbon_source))+geom_jitter(width=0.2)+
  stat_summary(fun=mean, geom="line", size=1)+
  stat_summary(fun.data = mean_se, geom="ribbon", color="transparent", alpha=0.3)+
  ylim(0,3)+
  scale_fill_discrete()+ # this sets color parameters for the mean_se ribbon
  scale_color_discrete()+ # this sets color parameters for the lines
  as_md_theme(my_theme)+ # this applies our theme from above to the plot
  ylab("OD590") + xlab("Time (Hrs)") + # here are our axis labels
  labs(color="",fill="") + # these would label our legend
  ggtitle("")+ # this would label the plot itself
  facet_wrap(~carbon_source)
  
plot(growth_all.p)

We finally get an overall look at our positive hits

  • Are there some carbon sources that support more growth than others?
  • Are each of the three replicates consistent?

How many positive carbon sources were there across groups?

pos_list<-list(g1_pos.m,g2_pos.m,g3_pos.m,g4_pos.m,g5_pos.m,g6_pos.m)

this command is getting the number of rows for each list of positive hits and then dividing by the number of time points (remember it’s a long format data frame) as well as the number of replicates, which was three

pos_num<-lapply(pos_list, function(x) (nrow(x)/(3*3)))

Let’s make a plot and see how many hits there were by group

pos.p<-ggplot(data.frame(sapply(pos_num,c)), aes(y=sapply.pos_num..c., x=rownames(data.frame(sapply(pos_num,c)))))+geom_point()+
  ylim(0,20)+
  as_md_theme(my_theme)+
  ylab("Positive Carbon Sources") + xlab("Group #") + labs() +
  ggtitle("")

plot(pos.p)
